---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { TAX_YEAR } from '../lib/constants';
import { STATES, getAllStateSlugs, getStateBySlug } from '../data/state-meta';

const title = `Sales Tax Calculator ${TAX_YEAR}: State & Local Rates by State`;
const description = `Calculate ${TAX_YEAR} sales tax for any US state and city. See combined state and local tax rates, exemptions, and total purchase cost. Free sales tax estimator.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'How is sales tax calculated?',
    answer: `Sales tax is calculated by multiplying the purchase price by the combined tax rate (state + local). For example, a $100 purchase with a 7.25% combined rate would include $7.25 in sales tax for a total of $107.25. Some states exempt certain items like groceries or clothing.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Which states have no sales tax?',
    answer: `Five states have no statewide sales tax: Alaska, Delaware, Montana, New Hampshire, and Oregon. However, Alaska allows local jurisdictions to impose their own sales taxes, so some areas in Alaska do collect local sales tax.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between state and local sales tax?',
    answer: `State sales tax is set by the state government and applies uniformly across the state. Local sales tax is additional tax imposed by counties, cities, or special districts. The combined rate (state + local) is what you actually pay at checkout and can vary significantly within a state.`,
  },
  {
    question: 'Are online purchases subject to sales tax?',
    answer: `Yes. Following the 2018 Supreme Court decision in South Dakota v. Wayfair, states can require online retailers to collect sales tax even if they have no physical presence in the state. Most states now require online sellers meeting certain revenue or transaction thresholds to collect and remit sales tax.`,
  },
];

const stateEntries = Object.entries(STATES)
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, ...s }))
  .sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-gradient-to-b from-navy-50 to-white px-4 pb-8 pt-10 dark:from-slate-900 dark:to-slate-950 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl text-center">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-white">
        Sales Tax Calculator {TAX_YEAR}
      </h1>
      <p class="mx-auto mt-4 max-w-2xl text-lg text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
        Calculate sales tax for any US state and city. See state, local, and combined rates for {TAX_YEAR}.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- State selector -->
  <section class="px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-8 shadow-sm dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-800">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Calculate Sales Tax</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
          Select your state below to see sales tax rates, local rate variations, and exemptions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- State grid -->
  <section class="px-4 py-12 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-7xl">
      <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        Sales Tax by State
      </h2>
      <div class="grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-4">
        {stateEntries.map((s) => (
          <a
            href={`/sales-tax-calculator/${s.slug}/`}
            class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-slate-700 transition hover:border-navy-300 hover:bg-navy-50 hover:text-navy-700 dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-800 dark:text-slate-300 dark:hover:border-navy-600 dark:hover:bg-slate-700 dark:hover:text-navy-400"
          >
            {s.name}
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content -->
  <section class="border-t border-slate-200 px-4 py-16 dark:border-slate-800 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="prose prose-slate dark:prose-invert mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 id="how-sales-tax-works-in-america">How Sales Tax Works in the United States</h2>
      <p>
        Sales tax is one of those everyday financial realities that most Americans interact with constantly but rarely think about deeply. Every time you buy a cup of coffee, a new shirt, or a piece of furniture, the price you see on the tag is almost never the price you actually pay at the register. The difference, of course, is sales tax, a consumption-based levy charged as a percentage of the purchase price and collected by retailers on behalf of state and local governments. While the concept is simple enough, the American sales tax system is remarkably complex, with different rates, exemptions, and rules in virtually every jurisdiction. Understanding how sales tax actually works can help you make smarter purchasing decisions, especially for large-ticket items, and gives you a clearer picture of your true cost of living.
      </p>

      <h2 id="no-federal-sales-tax">Why There Is No Federal Sales Tax</h2>
      <p>
        The United States is one of the few developed nations that does not impose a national sales tax or value-added tax. This is not an accident of history but a deliberate structural choice rooted in the American federal system. The Constitution grants Congress the power to levy taxes, and while there has been periodic debate about implementing a national sales tax or consumption tax to replace or supplement the income tax, these proposals have never gained enough political traction to become law. The primary objection has always been that sales taxes are regressive, meaning they take a larger percentage of income from lower-income households who spend most of what they earn compared to wealthier households who save and invest a larger share.
      </p>
      <p>
        Instead, sales tax authority in the United States resides with state and local governments. Each state sets its own base rate, its own rules for which goods and services are taxable, and its own administration and collection procedures. On top of the state rate, counties, cities, special districts, and transit authorities can layer additional local taxes, creating a patchwork of rates that vary not just state by state but block by block in some metropolitan areas. This decentralized approach gives local governments an important revenue tool but creates significant complexity for businesses that operate across multiple jurisdictions and for consumers trying to predict what they will actually pay.
      </p>

      <h2 id="state-and-local-sales-tax-rates">State and Local Sales Tax Rates Across the Country</h2>
      <p>
        State sales tax rates range from zero in the five states that impose no general sales tax to 7.25 percent in California, which has the highest base state rate. Tennessee, Indiana, Mississippi, and Rhode Island round out the top five with state rates at or above 7 percent. But the state rate only tells part of the story. When local taxes are added, the combined rate in many jurisdictions climbs significantly higher. Louisiana, for instance, has a state rate of only 4.45 percent but some of the highest combined rates in the country because parishes and municipalities add substantial local levies, pushing total rates above 12 percent in some areas. Similarly, Alabama's modest 4 percent state rate belies combined rates that can exceed 11 percent in certain cities.
      </p>
      <p>
        The variation in combined rates within a single state can be striking. In Texas, the state rate is 6.25 percent, but combined rates range from 6.25 percent in areas with no local tax to 8.25 percent in most major cities, an 8.25 percent cap being the maximum allowed by state law. In Colorado, the state rate is just 2.9 percent, but Denver's combined rate exceeds 8.8 percent when all local levies are included. This intra-state variation means that where exactly you make a purchase within a state can meaningfully affect what you pay, which is why border areas between jurisdictions with different rates sometimes see shopping patterns shift toward the lower-tax side.
      </p>

      <h2 id="sales-tax-exempt-items">Tax-Exempt Items and Why States Treat Certain Goods Differently</h2>
      <p>
        Not everything you buy is subject to sales tax, and the exemptions are one of the most policy-revealing aspects of each state's tax code. The most common exemption is for grocery food, which is fully exempt from sales tax in the majority of states that impose a general sales tax. States exempt groceries because food is a necessity and taxing it disproportionately burdens lower-income residents. However, the definition of what counts as grocery food versus prepared food or snacks varies by state and can lead to absurd distinctions. In some states, a bagel purchased at a bakery is tax-free, but the same bagel with cream cheese applied by the baker is taxable as prepared food.
      </p>
      <p>
        Prescription medications are exempt in nearly every state, reflecting the policy judgment that taxing healthcare necessities is inappropriate. Most states also exempt non-prescription medications, though a few do tax over-the-counter drugs. Clothing exemptions are less common but exist in a handful of states including Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and New York, where basic clothing items are exempt below certain price thresholds. In New York, clothing and footwear items priced under $110 each are exempt from the state sales tax, a provision designed to reduce the tax burden on essential wardrobe needs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Several states hold annual sales tax holidays, temporary periods when certain categories of purchases are exempt from sales tax. These holidays typically occur in late summer before the school year begins and exempt items like school supplies, clothing, computers, and sometimes hurricane preparedness supplies in coastal states. While the savings on individual purchases are modest, the cumulative benefit for families doing back-to-school shopping can be meaningful. Check your state's specific rules, as the eligible items and price limits vary significantly.
      </p>

      <h2 id="sales-tax-cost-of-living-impact">The Impact of Sales Tax on Your Cost of Living</h2>
      <p>
        Sales tax is often an afterthought in cost of living discussions, which tend to focus on housing, income taxes, and healthcare. But sales tax is a real and persistent drain on purchasing power that compounds over the course of a year. A household spending $50,000 annually on taxable goods and services in a jurisdiction with a combined rate of 9 percent pays $4,500 per year in sales tax. That same household in a state with no sales tax keeps that entire $4,500. Over a decade, the difference amounts to $45,000 in pre-tax spending power, a sum that could fund a significant portion of a retirement account or a down payment on a home.
      </p>
      <p>
        The impact is not uniform across income levels. Lower-income households spend a higher proportion of their income on consumption, which means sales tax consumes a larger share of their earnings compared to wealthier households who save or invest a significant portion. This regressivity is the central criticism of sales taxes and the reason many economists prefer progressive income taxes as a more equitable way to fund government services. Some states attempt to mitigate the regressivity by exempting groceries, clothing, and medications, as discussed above, but even with these exemptions, sales tax remains a greater burden proportionally on those with less income.
      </p>
      <p>
        When evaluating the total tax burden of living in a particular state, sales tax must be considered alongside income tax, property tax, and other levies. A state like Tennessee has no income tax on wages but imposes a 7 percent state sales tax with local additions pushing combined rates above 9.5 percent in some areas. A state like Oregon has no sales tax at all but imposes a state income tax with a top marginal rate near 10 percent. Which state offers the lower overall tax burden depends entirely on your income level, spending patterns, and housing costs. Use our <a href="/">paycheck calculator</a> to see how income taxes affect your take-home pay, and our <a href="/cost-of-living-calculator/">cost of living calculator</a> to compare overall expenses across cities.
      </p>

      <h2 id="online-sales-tax-after-wayfair">Online Sales Tax After the Wayfair Decision</h2>
      <p>
        For years, online shopping offered a practical way to avoid sales tax. Under the 1992 Supreme Court ruling in Quill Corp. v. North Dakota, states could only require retailers to collect sales tax if the retailer had a physical presence, known as nexus, in the state. This meant that buying from an out-of-state online retailer with no local warehouse or office was effectively tax-free for the consumer, even though technically the consumer owed use tax on the purchase. In practice, almost nobody voluntarily paid use tax on online purchases, and enforcement was essentially impossible for individual consumer transactions.
      </p>
      <p>
        Everything changed in June 2018 when the Supreme Court decided South Dakota v. Wayfair, Inc., overturning the physical presence requirement. The Court ruled that states could require out-of-state retailers to collect and remit sales tax based on economic nexus rather than physical nexus. Economic nexus is typically triggered when a seller exceeds a threshold of sales revenue or transaction volume into a state, often set at $100,000 in annual sales or 200 transactions. Within two years of the Wayfair decision, virtually every state with a sales tax had enacted economic nexus laws, and today all major online retailers, including Amazon, collect sales tax in every state that imposes one.
      </p>
      <p>
        The Wayfair decision fundamentally leveled the playing field between online and brick-and-mortar retailers and generated billions in additional state revenue. For consumers, it means that the price advantage of online shopping from a sales tax perspective has been almost entirely eliminated. There are still narrow circumstances where sales tax may not be collected, such as purchases from very small sellers who do not meet nexus thresholds, or purchases from individuals through platforms like Craigslist or Facebook Marketplace. However, even marketplace facilitators like eBay, Etsy, and Amazon Marketplace are now required in most states to collect tax on third-party sales.
      </p>

      <h2 id="use-tax-obligations">Use Tax: The Tax Most People Do Not Know They Owe</h2>
      <p>
        Use tax is the companion to sales tax and applies to purchases where sales tax was not collected at the point of sale. If you buy a piece of furniture from an out-of-state seller who does not collect your state's sales tax, you technically owe use tax on that purchase at your state's sales tax rate. The same applies to purchases made in other states. If you live in a state with an 8 percent sales tax rate and buy a laptop in a state with a 5 percent rate, you theoretically owe the 3 percent difference as use tax in your home state.
      </p>
      <p>
        In practice, use tax compliance by individual consumers has historically been abysmal, with estimates suggesting that fewer than 2 percent of eligible consumers voluntarily report and pay use tax on their income tax returns. The Wayfair decision reduced the scope of use tax liability by ensuring that most online purchases now have sales tax collected at the point of sale. However, use tax obligations still arise for purchases from small online sellers below nexus thresholds, purchases made across state lines, and items bought from individuals. Several states have added a use tax line to their income tax returns and some have even implemented audit programs targeting high-value purchases like vehicles, boats, and aircraft that cross state lines without proper tax payment.
      </p>

      <h2 id="states-with-no-sales-tax">States With No Sales Tax and What That Means for Residents</h2>
      <p>
        Five states impose no general sales tax at all: Alaska, Delaware, Montana, New Hampshire, and Oregon. Living in one of these states means the price on the shelf is the price you pay at checkout, which provides a genuine quality-of-life benefit beyond the raw dollar savings. For large purchases like appliances, electronics, or vehicles, the savings can be substantial. A $40,000 car purchased in Oregon saves approximately $3,400 compared to buying the same car in a state with an 8.5 percent combined sales tax rate.
      </p>
      <p>
        However, these states are not tax havens in the broader sense. Oregon compensates for its lack of sales tax with one of the highest income tax rates in the country, with a top marginal rate of 9.9 percent on taxable income above $125,000 for single filers. New Hampshire has no income tax on wages but imposes relatively high property taxes, with an average effective rate above 1.5 percent. Delaware has no sales tax and relatively moderate property taxes but levies a gross receipts tax on businesses that is often passed through to consumers in the form of higher prices.
      </p>
      <p>
        Alaska is a unique case. While there is no state sales tax, Alaska law allows municipalities to impose local sales taxes, and many do. Juneau, for example, levies a 5 percent sales tax, while Anchorage has no local sales tax. So the sales tax experience in Alaska depends entirely on which city or borough you are in. Additionally, Alaska residents receive an annual Permanent Fund Dividend check from the state's oil revenue investments, which effectively offsets some portion of any local taxes paid. The bottom line is that the presence or absence of sales tax is just one piece of the overall tax picture, and decisions about where to live should consider the total tax burden including income, property, and sales taxes together. Use our <a href="/take-home-comparison/">take-home comparison tool</a> to see how your total tax picture changes across different states.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQs -->
  <section class="px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>
      <dl class="space-y-6">
        {faqs.map((faq) => (
          <div class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 p-6 dark:border-slate-700">
            <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">{faq.question}</dt>
            <dd class="mt-2 text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">{faq.answer}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
